63rd Drive (formerly Penelope Avenue), at the N.E. corner of Austin Street, showing the Miller house of 1860. In 1909 it was located just north of the Long Island Railroad right of way. If it is still standing in 1938 it would be located at the first mentioned location. Other owners were J. Miller in 1873 and Herman Miller from 1896 to 1909.

April 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster

63rd Drive, north side between Austin Street (left) and Wetherold Street (right) showing two homes in existence after 1852 but prior to 1860. Other owners of this property were Mrs. Zeiler in 1873, one Ziler in 1891, M. Keppler in 1896 to 1909, and M. Zeiler in 1923. Both houses were destroyed by fire in 1923 or Jan. 1923.

April 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

63rd Drive, east side, north from Austin to Booth Streets, Rego Park, showing the Our Savior Evangelical Church and Public School No. 139. The church is between Austin and Wetherole Streets, and the school between Wetherole and Booth Streets. The 1929 Hyde atlas of Queens shows the church to have been at the N.W. corner of Wetherole Street, across the way from its present location. This edifice, then, is either a new one, or the old one was moved from its former site.

P. L. Sperr

May 24, 1935
Views 1,2
